Both proposed elements do not have any spurious zero-energy mode and their stiffness matrices are evaluated with 'full' numerical integration, i.e. 3 x 3 Gauss integration, in the rs plane for the MITC9 element, and 4 x 4 for the MITC16 element. According to the numerical results, the proposed elements are free of locking and perform quite effectively.
